29 CFR Part 1915 







Confined and Enclosed Spaces and Other Dangerous Atmospheres in Shipyard Employment 



<AGENCY>
AGENCY:

 Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA), Department of Labor.

 

</AGENCY>
<ACTION>
ACTION:

 Final rule. 






</ACTION>
<SUMMARY>
SUMMARY:

 The previous Subpart B of part 1915 sets out requirements for work in explosive and other dangerous atmospheres in
vessels and vessel sections and applies to shipbuilding, ship repairing, and shipbreaking operations and to related
employment. The final rule being promulgated today extends the protection afforded by these previous rules to employees
entering any confined or enclosed space or working in any other dangerous atmosphere in or out of a shipyard. The final
rule also simplifies and clarifies some of the requirements in the previous standards. 



The final rule includes requirements for a shipyard competent person, a Marine Chemist, a Certified Industrial hygienist,
or a Coast Guard authorized person to evaluate conditions within a confined or enclosed space and to institute measures
to ensure that entrants are protected. It also contains requirements for posting unsafe spaces, for safe performance
of cleaning, cold work, and hot work, and for classifying a person as a shipyard competent person.

 

</SUMMARY>
